04426nam a22005055i 9780773568532DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20002000xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735685327 a10.1515/97807735685322doi  a(DE-B1597)655226  a(OCoLC)180773060  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1035.J5bB52 2000eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a971/.0049241 aBialystok, Franklin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDelayed Impact :bThe Holocaust and the Canadian Jewish Community /cFranklin Bialystok. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (340 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: “A community of memory” -- t“The warm safety of North America”: The Holocaust and Canadian Jews in the 1930s and 1940s -- tGreener and Gayle: The Arrival of Survivors in the Late 1940s -- t“Europe’s ghosts in Canadian living rooms”: The Canadian Jewish Community in the 1950s -- t“The disease of anti-Semitism has again become active”: The Community and the Hate-Mongers in the Early 1960s -- t“A cleavage in the community”: The Toronto Jewish Community in the 1960s -- t“The Jewish Emptiness”: Confronting the Holocaust in the Late 1960s and Early 1970s -- t“Were things that bad?” The Holocaust Enters Community Memory -- t“A crucible for the community”: The Landmark Events of 1985 -- tConclusion: The Holocaust is not Joseph -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBialystok begins by examining the years immediately following World War II, showing that Canadian Jews were not psychologically equipped to comprehend the enormity of the Holocaust. Unable to grasp the extent of the atrocities that had occurred in a world that was not theirs, Canadian Jews were not prepared to empathize with the survivors and a chasm between the groups developed and widened in the next two decades. He shows how the efflorescence of marginal but vicious antisemitism in Canada in the 1960s, in combination with more potent antisemitic outrages internationally and the threat to Israel's existence, led to an interest in the Holocaust. He demonstrates that with the politicization of the survivors and the maturation of the post-war generation of Canadian Jews in the 1980s, the memory of the Holocaust became a pillar of ethnic identity. Combining previously unexamined documents and interviews with leaders in the Jewish community in Canada, Bialystok shows how the collective memory of an epoch-making event changed in reaction to historical circumstances. His work enhances our understanding of immigrant adaptation and ethnic identification in a multi-cultural society in the context of the post-war economic and social changes in the Canadian landscape and sheds new light on the history of Canadian Jewry, opening a new perspective on the effects of the Holocaust on a community in transition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356853240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773568532423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773568532/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles